<div id="review_1516720217" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1516720217" />
    <a title="T S" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42886196-t-s"><img alt="T S" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609333977p2/42886196.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1516720217?book_show_action=true">Jan 19, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="T S" class="user" itemprop="url" name="T S" href="/user/show/42886196-t-s">T S</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/42886196-t-s?shelf=indie-faves">indie-faves</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/42886196-t-s?shelf=review-copy">review-copy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1516720217" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4171540234091026420">A serendipitous love story. <br/><br/>This is the sequel to our demons, best friends but can be read as a standalone. It&apos;ll be shame though, Ava and Sebastian are too cute to miss. <br/><br/>Now a days, I just find it so hard to get completely lost in a romance novel. I go in expecting nothing but a decent story, but 80% of the time I come out with a mouthful to complain about how the characters were pretentious, how the romance was nauseatingly cheesy, how their obsession was unhealthy. That&apos;s because authors hard</span>
  <span id="freeText4171540234091026420" style="display:none">A serendipitous love story. <br /><br />This is the sequel to our demons, best friends but can be read as a standalone. It'll be shame though, Ava and Sebastian are too cute to miss. <br /><br />Now a days, I just find it so hard to get completely lost in a romance novel. I go in expecting nothing but a decent story, but 80% of the time I come out with a mouthful to complain about how the characters were pretentious, how the romance was nauseatingly cheesy, how their obsession was unhealthy. That's because authors hardly do it right. This book is RIGHT. So good. After putting it down, I had a silly grin plastered on my face, I was so happy because it has everything that I love to read about in a Ya novel. Everything that makes me appreciate a wonderful story.<br /><br />Why this book is amazing:<br /><br />1) Friendship: is the solid base and it is something that most authors do not focus on, but Diana does. When our protagonists met, they were attracted to each other, but their bond was not solely based on physical attraction. They became friends. It made their relationship feel so real. Made me ship them harder, you know ;)<br /><br />Again, (2) Friendship and loyalty: I see many people abandoning their best friends for their love interests, and this trope seriously makes me burn with rage. I wanted to hug Collin for taking a route that was difficult and would seriously make some readers detest him, in my case: his decision and loyalty made me love him even more. <br /><br />(3) Hilarious moments, sibling unity, and a romance that feels genuine: This was as funny as it was poignant. I just loved Em and Lana's sibling bond, how they had  each other's back no matter what. It was beautiful. It made me tear up and smile like mad at the same time. There were so many swoon worthy ship moments, I cherished those scenes deeply. I loved Em's character development. Atta girl, finally gave up her mother's dreams in order to chase her own. <br /><br />Overall, I loved everything about LMWIG, it was so darn readable and everything was just lovable, and cute, and perfect. . . And Collin (Heart eyes. Heart eyes.) This author does fictional men very well, they are so thoughtful, charismatic, and other fictional douchebags could learn a thing or two from them. The writing is beautiful and oh, my MOST favourite part: Just like ODBF, Damn, the prologue of LMWIG came with a dash of melancholy and Bam: I was hooked. That's how you do it, Diana, hook 'em up the prologue itself.<br /><br /> If you haven't read this series up, you should. I highly recommend it, it's way too adorable ;)<br /><br /><br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="4171540234091026420" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


